### XDR Response Cases
- Microsoft Defender for Enpoint detects a malicious payload
  - victim receives malicous email(on personal email account, not protected by Defender for Office 365 (MDO) or opens an attachment from a USB drive)
  - malware infects computer(when the attachment is opened)
  - user is unaware the malware has infected the system
  - MDE detects attack, raises alert(to SOC), provides details about the threat
  - disable user access(from device)
  - MDE communicates with Intune
    - risk level(on this endpoint) has changed
  - Intune Compliance Policy(configured with an MDE risk level severity) is triggered), marks the account as non-compliant(with organizational poicy)
  - Conditional Access(created in Microsoft Entra ID) blocks user access to apps
  - MDE remediates threat
    - automated remediation
    - security analyst approval of automated remediation
    - analyst manual investigation of threat
    - across entire enterprise(and other MDE customers)
  - adds 'information on this attack' to Microsoft Threat Intelligence system
  - restores access
    - once infected devices are remediated
    - MDE signals Intune to change the device risk status
    - Microsoft Entra ID Condtional Access allows access to enterprise resources
  - remediates 'threat variants' in MDO and others
    - threat signals(in Microsoft Threat Intelligence)
      - used by Microsoft tools to secure 'other parts of an organization's attack surface'
  - Microsoft Defender for Cloud/MDO
    - use the threat signals to detect/remediate threats in email/office collaboration/Azure
  - Conditional Access knowns about device risk
    - MDE notifies Intune
    - Intune updates the compliance status of a device(in Microsoft Entra ID)
    - user is restricted from accessing corporate resources(including all new resource requests)
    - user is blocked from 'resources that support CAE'
    - user is stil able to do general internet producitivity tasks(Youtube, Wikipedia, anything that does not require corporate authentication)
  - Access Restored
    - MDE triggers Intune to update Microsoft Entra ID
    - Conditional Access restores user access to corporate resources
  - mitigates risk(to the organization)
  - ensures attackers(who might be in control of these devices) cannot access corportate resources
  - minimizes impact on user productivity
  - minimizes disruption on business processes

### Microsoft Defender XDR in a SOC
- assignments of responsibilities vary(based on factors such as organizational size)
- security operations are composed of several distinct functions
- each funtion/team has a primary focus area, collaborates with other functions/teams
- Automation
  - handle reactive alerts
  - near real-time resolution of known incident types(well-defined attacks that have been seen many times)
  - reduces manual effort
  - provides automated investigation
  - can prompt for human review before approving remediation sequences
- Triage(Tier 1)
  - rapid remediation(of a high volume of well-known incident types)
  - require expedient human judgement
  - approve automated remediation workflows
  - identify anomalous/interesting incidents that warrant escalation or consultation with investigation teams
  - 90% of incidents should be true positive
  - XDR produces majority of 'high-quality alerts'. Followed by user reported issues, classic log query based alerts and other sources
- Tool Integration
  - integration of XDR tools in Microsoft Defender XDR
  - allows for a single console(for endpoint/email/identity)
  - enables rapid discovery and remediation of phishing emails, malware, compromised accounts(before significant damage)
  - time saving technology
  - improves 'time to remediation'(in Microsoft CDOC)
- Focus
  - teams keep their focus on few technical areas/scenarios(user productivity, email, endpoint AV alerts
- Investigation and Incident Management(Tier 2)
  - escalation point from Triage(Tier 1)
  - directly monitors 'alerts that indicate more sophisticated attackers', alerts that trigger behavioral alerts, special case alerts related to business-critical assets
  - monitor for ongoing attack campaigns
  - periodically reviews the Triage team alert queue
  - proactively hunt(using XDR tools)
  - provides deeper investigation(into lower volume/more complex attacks), multi-stage attacks(conducted by human attack operators)
  - handles new/unfamiliar alert types
  - documents processes for Triage and automation(including alerts generated by Microsoft Defender Cloud, VMs, containers, Kubernetes, SQL databases
  - coordinates with other teams(legal, communications, leadership, business stakeholders)
- Hunt and Incident Management(Tier 3)
  - identify 'attackers that may have slipped through reactive detections'
  - handle major business-impacting events
  - hunts for undetected threats
  - assists with escalations/advanced forensics
  - refine alerts/automation
  - operate in hypothesis-driven models
- Threat Intelligence teams
  - provide context/insights
  - supports allo other functions
  - utilize TIP(in larger organizations)
  - reactive technical research(for active incidents)
  - proactive technical research into attacker groups, attack trends, high profile attacks, emerging techniques
  - strategic analysis, reserach and insights to inform business and technical processes
- Microsoft Security Graph
  - provides 'unified programmability model'
  - used to access data in Micrososft 365/Windows/Enterprise Mobility + Security
  - use the data in Microsoft Graph to build customized apps
  - offers single endpoint
  - use REST APIs/SDKs to access the endpoint/build apps
  - includes set of services(that manage user and device identity/access/compliance and security)
  - helps protect against data leakage/loss
  - exposes REST APIs/client libraries(to access data on cloud services):
    - Microsoft 365 core services:
      - Bookings/Calender/Delve/Excel/Purview eDiscovery/Search/OneDrive/OneNote/Outlook/Exchange/People/Planner/Sharepoint/Teams/To DO/Viva Insights
    - Enterprise Mobility + Security services
      - Advanced Threat Analytics/Advanced Threat Protection/Microsoft Entra ID/Identity Manager/Intune
    - Windows services
      - activities/devices/notifications/Universal Print
    - Dynamic 365 Business Central services
    - developers can use Security Graph to build security services, to:
      - integrate/correlate security alerts(from multiple sources)
      - stream alerts to SIEMs
      - automaticaly send threat indicators to Microsoft security solutions to enable alert/block/allow
      - unlock contextual data(to inform investigations)
      - discover opportunities to learn from data/train security solutions
  - Microsoft Graph Security API
    - (2) versions(Microsoft Graph REST API v1.0 and Beta)
      - both support advanced hunting(using 'runHuntingQuery' method in KQL)
      - beta provides new/enhanced APIs(still in preview status)
      - APIs in preview status are subject to change, may break existing scenarios without notice
    - intermediary service/broker
    - provides single programmatic interface
    - connects multiple Microsoft Graph Security providers
    - requests to the Microsoft Graph security API are 'federated'(to all applicable security providers)
    - results are aggregated then returned to the requesting application
  - Azure Sentinel
    - cloud-native SIEM
    - provides security analytics acrouss enterprise environment
    - collects data at cloud scale(across all users, devices, applications, infrastructure on premise and in multiple clouds)

### Advanced hunting example in Microsoft Defender XDR

POST https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/security/runHuntingQuery

{
    "Query": "DeviceProcessEvents | where InitiatingProcessFileName =~ \"powershell.exe\" | project Timestamp, FileName, InitiatingProcessFileName | order by Timestamp desc | limit 2"
}

- request is calling Microsoft Graph Security API endpoint "POST/security/runHuntingQuerty
- runs an 'advanced hunting KQL query'(against Microsoft 365 Defender)
- DeviceProcessEvents(advanced hunting table, for process creation and related events. Includes columns such as Timestamp, Filename and InitiatingProcessFilename)
- DeviceProcessEvnets(chooses 'the table to search')
- where InitiatingProcessFilename=~ "powershell.exe"(filters to 'rows where the intitating process was Powershell')
- "=~"(operator, case-insensitive string comparison(in KQL)
- project Timestamp, FileName, InitiatingProcessFileName(returns only those (3) columns)
- order by Timestamp desc(sorts newest first)
- limit 2(returns only the (2) most recent matching rows)


